In Postgres, you can use the check constraint feature to validate data. A check constraint is a rule that every row must satisfy. You can enforce this on a table by specifying the constraint during table creation or adding it later using an ALTER TABLE statement.

To restrict a geometry column to only contain polygons, you can create a check constraint on the table using the ST_IsPolygon(geometry) function. This function returns true if the geometry is a polygon and false otherwise. The constraint would look like:

CREATE TABLE my_table (
  geom geometry(POINT,4326) CHECK (ST_IsPolygon(geom))
);

ALTER TABLE my_table ADD CONSTRAINT polygon_constraint 
CHECK (ST_IsPolygon(geom));

Now, any attempt to insert a point, line or other non-polygon geometry into the geom column will result in an error. This ensures that the geometry column only contains valid polygon geometries.

