The Hamiltonian that describes this non-conservative system is
\begin{align}
	H(q,p) = \frac{p^2}{2m} + V(q)
\end{align}
where $q$ is the position, $p$ is the momentum, and $V(q)$ is the potential energy.
For this damped harmonic oscillator, the potential energy is
\begin{align}
	V(q) = \frac{1}{2}kq^2
\end{align}
where $k = m\Omega^2$ is the spring constant. The Hamiltonian equations of motion are
\begin{align}
	\dot{q} = \frac{\partial H}{\partial p} = \frac{p}{m}\\
	\dot{p} = -\frac{\partial H}{\partial q} = -kq-2\lambda p
\end{align}

The analysis we just did shows how to write a general Hamiltonian for any non-conservative system by introducing auxiliary variables (in this case, the velocity). This method extends to more complex systems with additional degrees of freedom.

