Yes, Node.js provides a built-in module called "stream" that allows you to create read and write streams, as well as transform streams. You can use the "ReadableStream" object from the "stream" module to implement a pull-based stream.

A pull-based stream reads data from an input source only when data is requested by the consumer. This is different from a push-based stream where the producer pushes data to the consumer without waiting for requests. Pull-based streams are more suited in scenarios where the consumer wants to process data at their own pace and does not want to be flooded with data.

Here is an example of how to implement a pull-based stream that reads data from a file:

```javascript
const fs = require('fs');
const stream = require('stream');

class PullBasedStream extends stream.Readable {
  constructor(filename) {
    super({
      objectMode: true // allow objects to be passed through the stream
    });

    this.filename = filename;

    // open file and set up readable stream
    fs.createReadStream(filename).pipe(this);
  }

  _read() {
    this.push(fs.readFileSync(this.filename));
  }
}

module.exports = PullBasedStream;
```

In this example, we extend the Readable class from the stream module and override the _read() method. The _read() method is called automatically by the stream system when the consumer requests data from the stream. Here, we are reading the entire file into memory using fs.readFileSync() and pushing the data to the consumer via the push() method.

To consume this pull-based stream, you can call the pipe() method of a Writable stream to connect it to the PullBasedStream instance:

```javascript
const PullBasedStream = require('./PullBasedStream.js');

// create PullBasedStream instance
const stream = new PullBasedStream('/path/to/file.txt');

// pipe Writable stream to PullBasedStream
process.stdout.pipe(stream);
```

In this example, we are piping the standard output stream to the PullBasedStream instance, which will then read the file one line at a time and print it to the console.

