```js
function getBoundingBox(svgObject) {
  if (svgObject.children && svgObject.children.length > 0) {
    let bb = { 
      x: Infinity,  y: Infinity,
      width: 0,     height: 0 
    };

    svgObject.children.forEach(child => {
      bb = mergeBoundingBoxes(bb, getBoundingBox(child));
    });

    return bb;
  } else {
    return svgObject.getBoundingClientRect();
  }
}

function mergeBoundingBoxes(b1, b2) {
  let x = Math.min(b1.x, b2.x); 
  let y = Math.min(b1.y, b2.y);
  let w = Math.max(b1.x + b1.width, b2.x + b2.width) - x;
  let h = Math.max(b1.y + b1.height, b2.y + b2.height) - y;

  return { x, y, width: w, height: h};
}
```
This algorithm recursively traverses the DOM tree of an SVG object, and uses a custom `mergeBoundingBoxes()` function to combine the bounding boxes of all child elements into one single bounding box that encapsulates the entire SVG object.

A simple way to achieve this using Jetpack Compose is by wrapping your child composable in a SizeAwareBox. This composable takes in two parameters: maxWidth and maxHeight. The width and height of the box will be determined based on these values. You can then size and position your child composable based on the available space within the box.

Your composable would look something like this:

@Composable
fun MyChildComposable() {
    // Your composable code here
}

@Composable
fun ParentComposable() {
    SizeAwareBox(modifier = Modifier.width(300.dp).height(200.dp)) {
        // ...
        MyChildComposable()
        //...
    }
}
